tlett and Lara Boggeman and Carolyn O’Connor and Rosa G. Castanon and Huaming Chen and Conor Fitzpatrick and Chongyuan Luo and Joseph R. Nery and Michael Nunn and Angeline C. Rivkin and Wei Tian and Bertha Dominguez and Tony Ito-Cole and Matthew Jacobs and Xin Jin and Cheng-Ta Lee and Kuo-Fen Lee and Paula Assakura Miyazaki and Yan Pang and Mohammad Rashid and Jared B. Smith and Minh Vu and Elora Williams and Tommaso Biancalani and A. Sina Booeshaghi and Megan Crow and Sandrine Dudoit and Stephan Fischer and Jesse Gillis and Qiwen Hu and Peter V. Kharchenko and Sheng-Yong Niu and Vasilis Ntranos and Elizabeth Purdom and Davide Risso and Hector Roux de Bézieux and Saroja Somasundaram and Kelly Street and Valentine Svensson and Eeshit Dhaval Vaishnav and Koen Van den Berge and Joshua D. Welch and Xu An and Helen S. Bateup and Ian Bowman and Rebecca K. Chance and Nicholas N. Foster and William Galbavy and Hui Gong and Lin Gou and Joshua T. Hatfield and Houri Hintiryan and Karla E. Hirokawa and Gukhan Kim and Daniel J. Kramer and Anan Li and Xiangning Li and Qingming Luo and Rodrigo Muñoz-Castañeda and David A. Stafford and Zhao Feng and Xueyan Jia and Shengdian Jiang and Tao Jiang and Xiuli Kuang and Rachael Larsen and Phil Lesnar and Yaoyao Li and Yuanyuan Li and Lijuan Liu and Hanchuan Peng and Lei Qu and Miao Ren and Zongcai Ruan and Elise Shen and Yuanyuan Song and Wayne Wakeman and Peng Wang and Yimin Wang and Yun Wang and Lulu Yin and Jing Yuan and Sujun Zhao and Xuan Zhao and Arun Narasimhan and Ramesh Palaniswamy and Samik Banerjee and Liya Ding and Dhananjay Huilgol and Bingxing Huo and Hsien-Chi Kuo and Sophie Laturnus and Xu Li and Partha P. Mitra and Judith Mizrachi and Quanxin Wang and Peng Xie and Feng Xiong and Yang Yu and Stephen W. Eichhorn and Jim Berg and Matteo Bernabucci and Yves Bernaerts and Cathryn René Cadwell and Jesus Ramon Castro and Rachel Dalley and Leonard Hartmanis and Gregory D. Horwitz and Xiaolong Jiang and Andrew L. Ko and Elanine Miranda and Shalaka Mulherkar and Philip R. Nicovich and Scott F. Owen and Rickard Sandberg and Staci A. Sorensen and Zheng Huan Tan and Shona Allen and Dirk Hockemeyer and Angus Y. Lee and Matthew B. Veldman and Ricky S. Adkins and Seth A. Ament and Héctor Corrada Bravo and Robert Carter and Apaala Chatterjee and Carlo Colantuoni and Jonathan Crabtree and Heather Creasy and Victor Felix and Michelle Giglio and Brian R. Herb and Jayaram Kancherla and Anup Mahurkar and Carrie McCracken and Lance Nickel and Dustin Olley and Joshua Orvis and Michael Schor and Greg Hood and Benjamin Dichter and Michael Grauer and Brian Helba and Anita Bandrowski and Nikolaos Barkas and Benjamin Carlin and Florence D. D’Orazi and Kylee Degatano and Thomas H. Gillespie and Farzaneh Khajouei and Kishori Konwar and Carol Thompson and Kathleen Kelly and Stephanie Mok and Susan Sunkin},
  journal={Nature},
  volume={598},
  number={7879},
  pages={86-102},
  publisher={Springer Science and Business Media LLC},
  year={2021},
  doi={10.1038/s41586-021-03950-0},
  url={https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-021-03950-0},
  abstract={Abstract Here we report the generation of a multimodal cell census and atlas of the mammalian primary motor cortex as the initial product of the BRAIN Initiative Cell Census Network (BICCN). This was achieved by coordinated large-scale analyses of single-cell transcriptomes, chromatin accessibility, DNA methylomes, spatially resolved single-cell transcriptomes, morphological and electrophysiological properties and cellular resolution input–output mapping, integrated through cross-modal computational analysis. Our results advance the collective knowledge and understanding of brain cell-type organization 1–5 . First, our study reveals a unified molecular genetic landscape of cortical cell types that integrates their transcriptome, open chromatin and DNA methylation maps. Second, cross-species analysis achieves a consensus taxonomy of transcriptomic types and their hierarchical organization that is conserved from mouse to marmoset and human. Third, in situ single-cell transcriptomics provides a spatially resolved cell-type atlas of the motor cortex. Fourth, cross-modal analysis provides compelling evidence for the transcriptomic, epigenomic and gene regulatory basis of neuronal phenotypes such as their physiological and anatomical properties, demonstrating the biological validity and genomic underpinning of neuron types. We further present an extensive genetic toolset for targeting glutamatergic neuron types towards linking their molecular and developmental identity to their circuit function. Together, our results establish a unifying and mechanistic framework of neuronal cell-type organization that integrates multi-layered molecular genetic and spatial information with multi-faceted phenotypic properties.},
}

